snippet.textDisplay:
Ok I need to say this solitary isn’t just for prison. I was in a boarding school where I was put in solitary for six months. My parents and I would ask one another a question every week things like what is happiness to you? Well I got a two page letter in return one week, that all but two sentences censored. “Besides that I guess we’re ok. We look forward to hearing from you soon. - mom and dad” I was reasonably upset but ok besides that. Censored letters was a normal thing. I never had one but I guess it was about time. So that Sunday I wrote them my letter. Said that I was sorry but my letter got censored so I can’t answer their question if they asked me one. The next letter I got back was them calling me a liar that my letter wasn’t blacked out, and saying I was ungrateful, that I was rude and insensitive. I didn’t know what I did. So I broke down and was crying before bedtime. My family rep asked me if I wanted to talk. I said no. A few minutes after shutdown my family rep and two large men came into my dorm. The men grabbed me and drug me into oss. I didn’t break any rules! I was crying , anyone would if their parents called you a liar when you were telling the truth, I was helpless, frustrated, but still knew better then breaking any rules. The only reason I know I was In there for six months is because I’m a female, and mother nature’s clock wouldn’t let me loose time. Over time I stopped talking to my parents and days turned into weeks then into months then years and years turned into a decade. Oss broke me.


I didn’t know what was in that letter until last summer. My mom was diagnosed with cancer. My parents asked me if I wanted to come home to spend time with them, in case mom didn’t make it. The school censored my mom telling me she had cancer. I didn’t survive oss. My brain is broken. All because a school didn’t like the idea that I could have hope of going home before they said it was ok. I lost time with my family because they played mind games.

snippet.textDisplay: You should loose that "reckless eyeballing" slang. Its origins came from Southern prisons and chain gangs and referred to a black man looking at a white woman and IF HE WAS LUCKY, the guy would go to jail. Over the decades, that term moved North and West among African Americans in prison and ex-con social circles.

snippet.textDisplay: After doing a decade in prison and nearly 24 months of that (one 18month straight bit) in the hole I have to say this video might apply to maybe generously 5% of those who do time.   Post release issues are far more complex and far more subtle. Institutionalization is real but for the non convict it’s easily overcome.   And doing time in the hole ain’t that bad as it’s nice to take a break from the ignorance, drama and gangs periodically and catch up on your reading.

snippet.textDisplay: This is only somewhat accurate. You would not spend your first day in prison in solitary confinement. You would be in a reception center which can be worse as they put all levels of offenders in the same building. You usually go to solitary  for  violent acts where you go to hearings to see where you go from there. What is correct is solitary and prison life in general is very stressful and can be very alienating. Yes, I have been to prison.
